## Minutes of December 2nd, 2024

## LULULEMON ATHLETICA INC.

## PEOPLE, CULTURE AND COMPENSATION COMMITTEE

Minutes of the meeting held on December 2, 2024 at 1 Hotel Brooklyn, New York City

MEMBER ATTENDEES:     EMILY WHITE (Chair) MICHAEL CASEY ISABEL MAHE KATHRYN HENRY

INVITEES:

MARTI MORFITT (Chair of the Board) CALVIN MCDONALD (Chief Executive Officer) SUSAN GELINAS (Chief People &amp; Culture Officer) SHANNON HIGGINSON (Chief Legal &amp; Compliance Officer) ANGELA WRIGHT (VP, Health, Wealth &amp; Mobility) ERIN NICHOLAS (Corporate Secretary) MICHAEL OCLARAY (WTW) via Zoom

## 1. Call to Order

Emily White, Chair of the People, Culture and Compensation Committee (the 'Committee') of the Board of Directors (the 'Board') of lululemon athletica inc. (the 'Company'), called the meeting to order at approximately 9:00 a.m. Eastern time.  Ms. Nicholas acted as recording secretary for the meeting.

## 2. Approval of Minutes of Prior Meetings

The Committee reviewed and discussed the minutes of the meeting of the Committee held on September 4, 2024 which had been previously circulated to the members of the Committee.  Following discussion, the Committee unanimously approved such minutes.

## 3. Annual Review of SSC Bonus Plan Design

Ms. Gelinas discussed with the Committee the proposed plan design of the Company's short term incentive plans for the Store Support Centre ('SSC') for fiscal 2025, including changes proposed for fiscal 2025. She also provided an update on current tracking for the fiscal 2024 bonus and for the outstanding PSU cycles. Following discussion, the Committee approved the Company's proposed fiscal 2025 SSC bonus plan design.

## 4. Review of Annual Equity Plan Design

Ms. Wright discussed with the Committee the proposed equity plan design for fiscal 2025 previously circulated to the Committee and advised that there are no changes proposed for the plan design as compared to fiscal 2024. She discussed the proposed fiscal 2025 equity targets and mix as well as the updated guidelines for executive equity tier levels and some benchmarking information reviewed by management. Following discussion, the Committee approved the equity plan design as proposed for fiscal 2025.

## 5.  Review and approve proposed equity grants for the quarter

The Committee reviewed and discussed equity awards and the related resolutions proposed by management for SVP level and above employees. Ms. Wright provided the Committee with an update on the total equity spend to date in fiscal 2024, including the equity spend for SVP and above level employees and the equity pool delegated for the CEO for awards made to employees below the level of SVP, as well as the estimated number of units to be granted and the remaining equity budget for the year. Following this discussion, the Committee resolved as follows:

## 6. Equity Plan Terms and Conditions, Equity grant policy and guidelines for upcoming fiscal year

Ms. Wright discussed with the Committee the results of the annual review of the Company's 2023 Equity Incentive Plan summary, equity grant policy and equity grant agreements for fiscal 2025. She outlined the minor edits to the equity grant policy and the revisions to the equity grant agreements. Following discussion, the Committee approved the proposed changes and recommended that the proposed changes to the Company's equity grant agreements be approved by the Board.

## 7. Board of Director Compensation

Ms. Wright discussed with the Committee management's review of the Company's current non-employee director compensation plan (the 'Plan'). She discussed the information management used to benchmark the Company's current Plan and discussed the rationale for the review, including to ensure market competitiveness of the Plan, and the Committee's previous decision to only make changes to the Plan every two years. She also discussed how the Plan benchmarks against the Company's new executive compensation peer group and compensation trends in this area. Following discussion, the Committee agreed to review the Plan next year and make changes then if appropriate.

## 8. Retirement Provisions

Ms. Gelinas discussed with the Committee management's review of the Company's retirement provisions, the rationale for such review, and some proposed changes in that area, including updated terms and conditions of equity treatment upon retirement to align with market practice and an updated retirement definition. She also discussed the timing of the proposed changes and when they would take effect. Following discussion, the Committee asked management to further review the proposed provisions and come back to the Committee for approval at a later date.

## 9. Health &amp; Wealth Committee Charter

Ms.  Wright  discussed  the  updated  Health  and  Wealth  Committee  Charter previously circulated to the Committee. She discussed the rationale for updating the Charter and the key changes being proposed. She also discussed a change to the membership  of  the  Health  and  Wealth  Committee,  with  Ms.  Nicholas  stepping down from  that  committee.  Following  discussion,  the  Committee  approved  the updated  Charter  and  the  change  in  membership  to  the  Health  and  Wealth Committee and agreed to recommend such changes to the Board.

## Ms. Higginson left the meeting.

## 10.  SLT Compensation Review

Ms. Gelinas and Ms. Wright discussed with the Committee the initial results of the review of the compensation for the executives that report directly to the CEO.  They advised that management was not looking for approval for new salary levels for fiscal 2025 at this meeting, rather management would come back at the Committee's next meeting with pay recommendations for fiscal 2025 for the Committee's consideration and approval. The Committee discussed the Company's compensation philosophy at the senior executive level as well as the positioning of the members of the senior leadership team as compared to benchmark information. A discussion followed.

## Ms. Higginson rejoined the meeting.

## 11. Review of Available Reserve and Dilution Levels

Ms. Wright discussed with the Committee the available share reserve and dilution levels from the 2023 Plan and, following discussion, the Committee determined that both are at acceptable levels. The Committee also discussed the Company's Black-Scholes value.

## 12. Fiscal 2024 Year-End Base Pay Adjustment Budget

Ms. Wright discussed with the Committee the fiscal 2024 year-end budget for base pay adjustments including merit, market adjustments and promotions. She also discussed benchmarking completed by the Company in this area and proposed percentage increases in the various areas of the business and by country. Following discussion and questions from the Committee, the Committee determined the proposed budget was reasonable.

## Mr. McDonald left the meeting

Ms. Gelinas discussed with the Committee the initial results of Mr. McDonald's compensation review, including how his current market positioning compares to the Company's new peer group, his equity mix and his equity walkaway value. The Committee discussed some potential changes that could be made to Mr. McDonald's compensation for fiscal 2025 and a discussion followed. Ms. Gelinas advised the Committee that any recommended CEO compensation changes will be brought forward for discussion and approval at the Committee's next meeting.

## 14. CEO FY24 Performance &amp; FY25 Goal Setting

Ms. Gelinas discussed with the Committee the timeline, process and key dates with respect to Mr. McDonald's fiscal 2024 performance evaluation and compensation review and his fiscal 2025 goal setting.

Ms. Wright left the meeting.

Ms. Gelinas left the meeting.

- o Consistent with prior years; we have considered AOP; consensus; the basis points spread in year-over-year growth rates; probability of achievement; and peer group comparisons.

- ▪ Our historical performance and historical goals are shown for comparison in Appendices A and B.

- o We will continue to deliver on our pay-for-performance philosophy; with our YoY growth rates at target and stretch being generally positioned in the top quartile of our industry peer group forecasts. While our operating income target is positioned below median against our peers; it is reflective of the planned one-time YoY operating margin deleverage. ## Financial Context

Our ability to achieve the proposed F2025 incentive targets is set within the F2024 and F2025 financial context and associated pressures outlined at the January Board meeting:

## 2024 Performance shifts/ management:

- o Expenses have been reduced by approximately $28OM, expanding the FY24 operating margin to 23.7%, compared to 23.2% in F2023.
- o F2024 sales have declined by approximately $5OOM+ since our initial plan; now trending at +8.3% (excluding Week 53).
- o In line with market practice; our GBR bonus payout is based on actual FX rates; while we adhere to constant currency for regions Consequently; our GBR bonus payout is approximately 81%, impacted by FX shifts since FY24 AOP planning:
- ▪ Holding FX constant to AOP planning rates; the payout would be 134%.

## F2025 Financial considerations:

- o The merchandising plan is set at $11.8B, with a 2.75% spread to AOP; offering limited upside based on current Revenue outlook reflective of inflection and inventory position:

## Extraordinary Events Discretion for Bonus Goals

Given uncertainties around tariffs and foreign exchange impacts on our business performance and bonus plans; we worked with WTW to understand anticipated market practice: We learned that:

- o Most companies are taking a wait-and-see approach and are not modifying their core incentive pay design; because it remains unknown if/when tariffs will be imposed and what the impacts will be.
- o Some companies are considering interim actions within the existing incentive design structure; such as reducing the threshold performance goal threshold goal at 80% of target goal rather than typical 85% of target goal) or shifting the LTI mix to increase the portion delivered in RSUs. (eg.-
- o Companies are generally not taking actions like those for 2020 at beginning of the pandemic (e.g , bifurcating the annual incentive plan into two 6 month plans).

WTW advises that; in addition to raising this topic now in Q1 and revisiting it mid-year; we reground on existing extraordinary itemslevents language within our Executive Bonus Plan and PSU plans; which enables the PCCC to apply discretion when approving bonus and PSU payouts if warranted.

- o Although the current Executive Bonus Plan and the SSC bonus plan documents are silent regarding the PCCC's use of discretion to adjust performance measures; the plans do give the Committee broad discretion to administer the plans; which likely includes consideration of an extraordinary event.
- o Under item 5, Bonus Determinations; the Executive Bonus Plan states the following:
- ▪ (a) Performance Goals. The Committee may establish performance goals that relate to financial; operational or other performance of the Company or any of its subsidiaries or divisions; to individual performance objectives of the participant; or to any other performance goal established by the Committee in connection with a potential bonus payment (the "Performance Goals"). Performance Goals may relate to annual; semi-annual quarterly or other performance periods established by the Committee; although it is generally expected that the Committee will establish annual performance periods under this plan. Following the completion of any performance period (at a time determined by the Committee in its sole discretion) the Committee will evaluate attainment of the Performance Goals. The Committee may revise or refine Performance Goals in its discretion:
- ▪ Under the item 4.2 of the PSU agreement; we state:
- · Adjustment to Performance Measures for Extraordinary Items: The Committee shall adjust Performance Measures; as it deems appropriate; to exclude the effect (whether positive or negative) of any of the following occurring after the grant of the Award: (a) a change in accounting standards required by generally accepted accounting principles or (b) any extraordinary; unusual or nonrecurring item: Each such adjustment; if any; shall be made solely for the purpose of providing a consistent basis from period to period for the calculation of the Performance Measures in order to prevent the dilution or enlargement of the Participants rights with respect to the Award.
- ▪ Our interpretation is that the unexpected effects of tariffs could be considered an "extraordinary; unusual or nonrecurring item:" We are seeking to get the Committee's perspective on this.

We plan to revisit this topic at our September meeting to update on how tariffs and FX rates may be impacting business performance:

## PEOPLE, CULTURE AND COMPENSATION COMMITTEE CHARTER

## PURPOSE

The People, Culture and Compensation Committee (the 'Committee') is a standing committee of the Board of Directors of lululemon athletica inc. (the 'Company'). The purpose of the Committee is to (1) discharge the responsibilities as delegated by the Board of Directors relating to compensation of independent members of the Board of Directors, the Company's chief executive officer ('CEO'), and the executive officers of the Company; (2) to assist the Board of Directors in establishing incentive compensation and equity-based plans and programs and administer those plans and programs; and (3) to perform such other duties and responsibilities specified in and consistent with this charter.

## MEMBERSHIP

Membership on the Committee shall be determined by the Board of Directors upon the recommendation of the Corporate Responsibility, Sustainability and Governance Committee (the 'CRSG Committee'). Committee members shall serve until their successors shall be duly elected and qualified. Unless a chairperson of the Committee is elected by the Board of Directors, the members of the Committee may designate a chairperson of the Committee by majority vote of the full Committee membership. The Board of Directors, in consultation with the CRSG Committee, may remove the entire Committee or any individual member of the Committee at any time with or without cause and may appoint an independent director to fill the vacancy for the remainder of the term.

The Committee shall be comprised of at least three members, each of whom shall meet the independence requirements of applicable law and the listing standards of The Nasdaq Stock Market, in each case as determined by the Board of Directors. Unless otherwise determined by the Board of Directors, each member of the Committee must also meet the requirements of a 'non-employee director' for purposes of Rule 16b-3 under the Securities Exchange Act of 1934, as amended (the 'Exchange Act').

## MEETINGS

- · The Committee's chairperson (or in his or her absence, a member designated by the Committee's chairperson) shall preside at each meeting of the Committee and set the agendas for Committee meetings. The Committee shall have the authority to establish its own rules and procedures for notice and conduct of its meetings so long as they are not inconsistent with the provisions of the Company's bylaws that are applicable to a committee of the Board of Directors.

- · In order to discharge its duties and responsibilities, the Committee shall meet as often as necessary to carry out its responsibilities. Any member of the Committee may call a special meeting of the Committee. Meetings of the Committee may be held in-person or via telephonic or video conference.
- · Except as otherwise provided by statute or this Charter, a majority of the members of the Committee shall be required to constitute a quorum for the transaction of business at any meeting, and the act of a majority of the Committee members present and voting at any meeting at which a quorum is present shall be the act of the Committee. Any action required or permitted to be taken at any meeting of the Committee may be taken without a meeting if all members of the Committee consent thereto in writing or by electronic transmission. All such writings or electronic transmissions shall be filed with the minutes of proceedings of the Committee.
- · The Committee may, in its discretion, invite other directors of the Company, members of the Company's management, or any other person whose presence the Committee believes to be desirable and appropriate to attend and observe meetings of the Committee. Individuals who are invited to attend meetings of the Committee shall (a) not participate in any discussion or deliberation of the Committee unless invited to do so by the Committee, and (b) not be entitled to vote on any matter brought before the Committee. The Committee may exclude from its meetings any person it deems appropriate.
- · The Committee shall maintain minutes or other records of meetings and activities of the Committee. Minutes of meetings of the Committee shall be distributed periodically to the full Board of Directors.
- · All action taken by the Committee (or any subcommittee thereof) shall be reported to the Board of Directors at the next meeting of the Board of Directors following such action. In addition, compensation matters may be discussed in executive session with the full Board of Directors during the course of the year.

## COMPENSATION PHILOSOPHY

The Company's compensation policies with respect to the executive officers of the Company are based on the principles that compensation should encourage sustained long-term performance. Compensation should, to a significant extent, be reflective of the financial performance of the Company, aligned with shareholders, and a significant portion of executive officers' compensation should be provided through long-term incentives. The Committee seeks to have compensation of the Company's executive officers set at levels that are competitive so that the Company may attract, retain and motivate highly qualified executive officers to contribute to the Company's success. In assessing overall compensation for executive officers, the Committee will consider (among other things) the Company's performance, relative stockholder return and industry position, market compensation data, awards given to the Company's executive officers in past years, and the recommendations of third-party consultants.

## DUTIES AND RESPONSIBILITIES

The following functions are the common recurring activities of the Committee in carrying out its responsibilities. These functions are set forth as a guide with the understanding that the Committee may diverge from this guide as appropriate given the circumstances.

## Executive Compensation.

- · The Committee shall periodically review and advise the Board of Directors concerning the Company's overall compensation philosophy, policies and plans, including a review of executive compensation practices and trends in order to assess the adequacy and competitiveness of the Company's compensation programs for the Company'sexecutive officers relative to comparable companies. The Committee shall review and approve appropriate companies to comprise any peer group (or groups) used for comparison purposes.
- · The Committee will review and recommend to the Board of Directors the compensation and other terms of employment of the Company's CEO and will evaluate the CEO's performance in light of relevant corporate performance goals and objectives. In determining the long-term incentive component of the CEO's compensation, the Committee should seek to achieve an appropriate level of risk and reward, taking into consideration the Company's performance and relative stockholder return, the potential benefits and costs to the Company of the award and such other criteria as the Committee deems advisable. The  CEO may not be present during the voting or deliberations regarding his or her compensation.
- · The Committee will review and approve the corporate performance goals and objectives related to the equity and incentive compensation of the Company's other executive officers (as that term is defined in Section 16 of the Exchange Act and Rule 16a-1 thereunder) and other senior management, as appropriate, that are periodically established. The Committee will determine and approve all elements of the compensation and other terms of employment of these executive officers and other senior management, as appropriate. The Committee shall consult with, and take into account the recommendations of the  CEO with respect to any matters concerning the performance and compensation of the Company's executive vice presidents and other direct reports of the CEO. The Committee may also review and approve any offers or pay changes to other highly compensated executives the Committee may designate from time to time. The CEO may be present during these deliberations.
- · The Committee shall review and recommend to the Board of Directors new or amended executive compensation programs, conduct an annual review of the operation of the Company's executive compensation programs to determine whether they are properly coordinated and achieving their intended purposes, support organization objectives and stockholder interests, can create a pay for performance linkage. The Committee will establish and periodically review policies for the administration of the executive compensation programs.

- · The Committee shall establish and periodically review policies with respect to management perquisites and special benefits, and review and approve the benefits provided to the Company's executive officers.

## Director Compensation.

Consistent with the executive compensation philosophy, the Committee seeks to have compensation of the Company's directors set at levels that are competitive so that the Company may attract, and retain qualified candidates, and align our directors' interest with those of our shareholders.

The Committee shall advise the Board of Directors with respect to proposed changes in the compensation of members of the Board of Directors or any committee thereof. In considering director compensation, the Committee may take into consideration the relative responsibilities of directors in serving on the Board of Directors and its various committees. The Committee may request that management or outside advisors report to the Committee periodically on the status of the Board of Directors' compensation in relation to other similarly situated companies. Directors who are Company employees shall not be compensated for their services as a director of the Company.

## Benefit and Incentive Plans.

The Committee shall review and approve material changes in the Company's incentivecompensation plans, equity-based plans, deferred compensation plans and authorize and approve significant changes in the design of the Company's retirement and welfare benefit plans, programs and arrangement, including, but not limited to, termination or adoption of material benefits plans, programs, or arrangements that cover large employee populations or that are primarily for the benefit of the Company's executive officers or executive vice presidents.

- · The Committee shall also review and make recommendations to the Board of Directors with respect to the Company's established criteria for the granting of options and other stock-based awards to eligible participants under such plans, including, without limitation, the Company's executive officers and other employees; review and approve the granting of options and other stock-based awards to eligible participants under such plans; and supervise administration of such plans.
- · The Committee shall recommend to the Board of Directors the terms of any incentive, equity or benefit plan that requires the approval of the Company's stockholders, including amendments thereof, and shall administer those plans on behalf of the Board of Directors.

## Employment Agreements.

The Committee shall review and recommend to the Board of Directors the terms of any employment agreements, severance arrangements, change-of-control protections and any other

compensatory arrangements for the Company's CEO. The Committee shall review and approve the terms of any employment agreements, severance arrangements, change-of-control protections and any other compensatory arrangements for the Company's other executive officers and senior management, as appropriate.

## Disclosure.

- · The Committee shall review and discuss with management the Company's disclosures under the 'Compensation Discussion and Analysis' (the 'CD&amp;A') portion of the Company's proxy statement relating to the annual meeting of stockholders, and based on such review and discussion, make a recommendation to the Board of Directors as to whether the CD&amp;A should be included in the Company's annual report on Form 10-K and the Company's proxy statement.
- · The Committee shall produce an annual Report of the Compensation Committee for the Company's annual report on Form 10-K and the Company's proxy statement, in compliance with applicable rules and regulations.
- · The Committee shall review and make recommendations with respect to shareholder, management and Board proposals on executive compensation matters. This includes assessing the results of the Company's advisory votes on executive compensation, making executive compensation decisions as recommendations to the Board of Directors based on those assessments, and making recommendations to the Board of Directors related to the 'say on pay' proposals required by Section 14A of the Exchange Act.

## Compensation Policies and Practices Relative to Risk.

- · The Committee shall periodically, but no less than annually, review the Company's compensation policies and practices to determine if there are risks presented that are reasonably likely to have a material adverse effect on the Company. This review will also consider the risk mitigating processes, steps and controls that the Company has in place.
- · The Committee shall determine whether disclosure of the Company's compensation policies and practices in this regard is required to be included in the Company's proxy statement under Item 402(s) of Regulation S-K of the Exchange Act, and, if such disclosure is required, shall review and discuss with management such disclosure and shall make a recommendation to the Board of Directors as to whether such disclosure should be included in the Company's proxy statement.
- · The Committee shall report to the Board of Directors the results of such evaluation and determination.

- · The Committee shall recommend to the Board of Directors stock ownership guidelines and recoupment policies for the Company's executive officers and nonemployee directors, and periodically assess such guidelines (including executive and nonemployee director progress toward the guidelines) and policies and recommend revisions, as appropriate.

## Talent Management and Succession Planning.

The Committee shall review with management, at least annually, a detailed report on succession planning and talent management that covers: the programs that support the growth and development of our current and future generations of leaders and our bench strength including identification of potential successors for each executive role, as well as other roles that are critical to the Company's success (including for the CEO in the case of an emergency). The Committee will also provide a report to the full Board annually on these matters.

## Diversity and Inclusion.

The Committee shall periodically review with management the Company's policies and practices with respect to diversity and inclusion.

## Committee Review.

The Committee shall conduct an annual review and evaluation of its own performance. The Committee shall report to the Board of Directors the results of such annual performance evaluation, which shall include a comparison of the performance of the Committee with the requirements of this Charter.

## Charter Review.

The Committee shall conduct an annual assessment of the adequacy of this Charter and annually recommend any proposed changes to the Board of Directors for approval.

## Investigation of Other Matters.

In discharging its oversight role, the Committee is empowered to investigate any matter brought to its attention.

## Stockholder Proposals.

The Committee shall review and make recommendations to the Board of Directors with respect to management's recommendations with respect to any stockholder proposals primarily addressing executive compensation matters for the Company's proxy materials.

## ACCESS TO RECORDS AND RESOURCES

The Committee will have the resources and authority necessary to discharge its duties and responsibilities. In carrying out its duties and responsibilities, the Committee shall have full access to any relevant records of the Company and may retain experts and outside consultants or

other advisors to advise the Committee. The Committee shall also have authority to obtain advice and assistance from internal or external legal, accounting or other advisors. The Committee shall have sole authority to engage, terminate and determine the independence, compensation and terms of engagement of any experts, outside consultants, external legal counsel, accounting or other advisors. Prior to selecting, or receiving advice from, any advisor, the Committee shall consider the independence of such advisor based on the independence factors listed in Nasdaq Rule 5605(d)(3); provided, however, that the Committee shall not be prohibited from obtaining advice from advisors that it determines are not independent. The Committee may also request that any officer or other employee of the Company, the Company's outside counsel or any other person meet with any members of, or consultants to, the Committee. The fees, expenses or compensation owed to any person retained by the Committee and any ordinary administrative expenses of the Committee incurred in carrying out its duties and responsibilities shall be borne by the Company.

Any communications between the Committee and legal counsel in the course of obtaining legal advice will be considered privileged communications of the Company and the Committee will take all necessary steps to preserve the privileged nature of those communications.

## DELEGATION OF DUTIES

The Committee shall be entitled to delegate any or all of its duties or responsibilities to a subcommittee of the Committee, to the extent consistent with the Company's certificate of incorporation, bylaws, and applicable laws and rules of the markets in which the Company's securities then trade. In addition, the Committee may authorize a person or body to (i) designate eligible individuals other than executive officers and directors to be the recipients of equity compensation and (ii) determine, within  the parameters established by the Committee or the Board of Directors, the size and terms of equity awards to be granted to each such recipient, to the extent consistent with the Company's certificate of incorporation, bylaws, and applicable laws and rules of the markets in which the Company's securities then trade; provided, however, that no officer may designate himself or herself as such a recipient. Any officer to whom such authority is delegated shall regularly report to the Committee on the grants so made. To the extent necessary to comply with Rule 16b-3, the 'non-employee directors,' acting as a subcommittee, shall have authority to act on behalf of the Committee.

## Retirement Provisions Review

## The intention of this document is to:

Outline our findings and recommended changes to our company-wide retirement provisions. Note that this item was initially discussed; however, not approved; at the December 2024 PCCC meeting. At that time; the Committee had a question about how we would treat equity in the final year of employment; which we have addressed in this updated version: We have also addressed the vesting schedule in China: No other changes have been made relative to the prior version presented to the Committee.

## This item is for Committee review and approval.

- o Updated terms and conditions of equity treatment upon retirement to align with market practice; and
- o Updated retirement definition:
- ▪ Both are proposed for F2026 implementation and subject to AOP funding:

## Summary:

We have reviewed the terms and conditions of our equity treatment upon retirement and confirmed that our current vesting provsion for RSUs and stock options is positioned below market practice: While our RSUs and stock options continue to vest for a period of 12 month, the market typically allows for full vesting for both RSUs and stock options Market data is shown in Appendix A

- o Therefore; we propose to update the treatment of RSUs and stock options; to better align with market.
- o The estimated cost of these changes is projected to be in the approximate range of $4-5M* for F2026 and $9-1OM* for F2027; the incremental cost is driven by all unvested RSUs and stock options continuing to vest post retirement; compared to 12months continued vesting under the existing policy.

To support more proactive retirement planning for employees; and to provide greater flexibility for us to hire later-in-career talent; we reassessed our retirement provisions including our retirement definition; annual bonus treatment; retirement savings plans; and postretirement health benefits:

- o We propose to change our retirement definition; to be used for equity treatment upon retirement; to a points-based system as the criterion (i.e. combining age and years of service) aligned with emerging market practice.
- o We propose implementing a points-based system where age and years of service must total at least 65 points; with a minimum age requirement of 50 years. Additionally; the existing criterion of 25 years of service will be maintained. In both scenarios; a mandatory notice period of six months will be required.
- ▪ This will replace the existing criteria of employees meeting the earlier of (i) 55 years of age &amp; 10 years of service or (ii) 25 years of service.
- ▪ As some employees would be eligible for retirement earlier; this results in an acceleration of their equity retirement expense and an incremental cost of approximately $9-1OM for F2026 and $1-2M for F2027.

(Summary continues on the following page)

*Estimated numbers are provided as an indication of magnitude and are subject to change based on future grant values; terminations; and detailed calculations by individual

Accounting note: If an employee's equity award continues to vest once they have retired; the related expense is recognized over the shorter of (a) the vesting period and (b) the time until they become retirement eligible: If an employee does not retire when they are eligible; the equity expense for any future grants would be expensed at the time of grant.

For bonus eligibility; the Termination Language change; as previously described in the Bonus item presented at the December 2024 meeting; will also support retirement planning: The criteria has changed from a notice-based to an employment-based trigger; allowing the employees to align their retirement date with our annual SSC bonus payout:.

Previously; an employee providing termination notice for any reason (i.e including retirement) prior to payment date (i.e, before April 25) would forfeit bonus: With the updated criteria; an employee may provide notice of termination prior to payment and will receive their bonus provided continue to be actively employed through payment date. they

Following a review of other retirement and benefits programs; we are not proposing any changes to the following:

- o Benefits: We currently do not offer post-retirement benefits; which is consistent with market trend (ie, due to unpredictable costs associated with self-insurance); although we do offer an option with our vendor partners for retiring employees to purchase limited benefit plans at preferred rates.

The proposed changes will apply to F2026 grants and beyond; while previous grants will adhere to the prior retirement definition and treatment:.

Our design for retirement treatment is based on our global philosophy and will apply to executives across all regions. As employees in China are subject to special administrative rules; treatment at retirement will require equity to accelerate upon date of retirement. This is consistent with local regulations and market practices and is outlined in our current grant agreements. Appendix B illustrates the treatment for employees in China

For equity granted in year of the employee announcing their intention to retire or retirement date; we propose will receive full value of the grant and will also receive the full vesting as intended (i.e no pro-ration or forfeitures of the employee's last equity grant). An example is shown in Appendix C. they

- o After reviewing market practice with our external partners; we have found market practice is variable; with no consistent treatment.
- o Allowing for the final grant to have the same full vesting treatment (ie, no pro-ration) enables transparent and proactive retirement planning and aligns with our overall intent which is to incentivize a long-term planning horizon and to reward employees for their contributions and service. From an administration perspective; it would be challenging to clawback or pro-rate grants if retirement notice was provided postgrant.

As noted, we are seeking approval on these changes now; and plan to implement the changes effective F2026. Our people and payroll systems are not currently configured to support these changes; so we will work through the necessary updates over the next year, prior to F2026.

## Retirement Equity Treatment

## Aligning to Market Practice

Following our review of market practice for equity treatment upon retirement; we have identified that our current treatment of RSUs and stock options is not aligned with market practice: While our RSUs and stock options continue to vest for a period of 12months; the most common market practice is to allow full vesting for both RSUs and stock options.

The recommendation for continued vesting of RSUs and stock options will allow employees to receive all outstanding RSUs and stock options. If approved; these changes would apply to F2026 grants and beyond.

PSUs will vest at end of performance cycle with actual payout (i_e , actual performance achieved in the last year of the performance cycle) | RSUs will continue to vest for 12 months following the date of retirement. | Stock options will continue to vest for 12 months following the date of retirement:. |

## Retirement Definition

## Intent

In recent years; we have hired later-in-career external leaders into senior roles to bring critical expertise to the organization and anticipate this continuing as we approach our next strategic cycle We believe that providing an updated equity offering at retirement will allow us to attract later-career talent and avoid the need for one-off or unique equity /cash elements; upon hire This approach allows for full realization of benefits for those with a shorter time horizon to retirement; as current equity treatment would be resignation treatment (ie, leading to forfeiture of unvested amounts). Additionally; it will help enable consistency in treatment:

## Definition

The current retirement definition has two criteria for eligibility; at the earlier of the employee meeting (i) 55 years old &amp; 10 years of service; or (ii) 25 years of service.

- o The current definition is designed to reward employees with long-term service. However, it does not enable hiring later-career employees and allowing them to receive equitable benefits; as those that do not meet the retirement definition would receive equity treatment that is akin to resignation: This is known; and leads to negotiations around alternatives (i.e , via cash or on-boarding awards); to address foregone value

The proposed definition will include the following criteria:

- A points-based system where age and years of service must total at least 65 points; with a minimum age requirement (i.e, 50 years) to mitigate potential risk associated with one retiring too early and moving to work for another company.

Or

- ii.

Finally; a 6-month notice period will be included in the definition to allow an orderly transition plan for the Company.

- o From a risk perspective; a long-tenured employee who becomes retirement eligible at a younger age may provide retirement notice and immediately work for competitor (i.e , following their 6 month notice period). Implementing a notice period should minimize the risk; and our non-compete provisions would still apply to the retiree; effective starting on their last working day.

## C Equity Granted in Year of Retirement

## Equity Treatment

For equity granted in year of the employee announcing their intention to retire or retirement date; we intend; with the Committee's alignment; for the last equity grant to be the full value (i.e., no pro-ration or forfeitures of the employee's last equity grant). Upon reviewing market practice with our vendors; we have concluded that there is no clear market practice. The following are considerations for providing full vesting of equity granted in year .

## Pros

## Cons

- ▪ Alignment: Allowing full grants will encourage a long-term perspective when planning and executing work
- ▪ Employee financial benefit Full vesting of the final grant will provide more financial benefit to the employee.
- ▪ Administration: We will not need to monitor a cut-off date for when equity granted in year can be kept or to be forfeited:.
- ▪ Date of Retirement: Employee's will have flexibility to plan a retirement date that best aligns with personal needs and business needs. This removes any "gaming of the system" , or executive's delaying retirement notice to better align with a grant date.
- ▪ Financial cost to the company: Allowing full vesting of the final grant will cost more using the standard SVP grant of $375K, we estimate that allowing full vesting for an SVP would cost the company approximately $187K more than if we were to truncate the final grant for someone working (e.g-
- · If we had a conservative retirement rate of 3%, the total cost would be ~$35OK-S4OOKyr .
- ▪ Administration: The administrative system is not set up to track pro-rated awards. Therefore; these awards will need to be pro-rated and tracked manually. It would be challenging to clawback or pro-rate the awards after it has been granted.

## Examples

- 1 In January; executive announces intention to retire in July; giving the required 6 months' notice The executive is still equity eligible to receive the full-value of their last equity grant in March and will receive continued vesting:
- 2 In April; executive announces intention to retire in October. The executive's last annual equity grant has already been granted in full in March and will receive continued vest.

## CEO Compensation Review

## The intention of this document is to:

Review and approve F2025 pay recommendations (base salary; bonus; and long-term incentives) for the CEO.

## This item is for Committee review and approval.

Below we outline potential considerations to Calvin's compensation for F2025, for discussion with the Committee:

- A base salary increase from $1.35M to $I.4M (3.7%) shifts base pay position from P5O to 55. o
- No change to target bonus of 200% of salary . o
- Increase of annual equity from SIIM to SI2M (+9%) would result in a total comp (incl. salary increase) of 7.6%. o
- Update his equity mix to 60% PSUs and 40% Options. o
- Hold his current SOG at 5x salary. o

## Summary:

Calvin has been in role for 6.5 years since his hire in August 2018. During Calvin's tenure; the business has delivered a strong performance; with an annualized TSR of 22.9% and an increase in market capitalization of ~$46.7B.

- o F2018 to F2024, Calvin's total direct compensation (TDC) CAGR was 8.7% and in absolute terms; has increased 65%, driven primarily through equity increases from $6M to SIIM.
- o Calvin's cash compensation has increased through moderate base salary increases from $1.2OM to $1.35M, and target bonus opportunity from 150% to 200%.

Calvin's current TDC of $15.05M is currently ranked at the 6Oth percentile in our peer group and positions him 9th out of 19 peers. We have outlined the following considerations for Calvin's F2025 compensation; to discuss with the Committee:

- o Moderate base salary increase to align with Company's target merit posture.
- o Increase his annual equity to strengthen market position:
- o Increase the weighting of PSUs of his equity mix to better align with market data (and from an institutional investor perspective would be considered "performance based").

The following appendices provide additional information to support this compensation review.

- o Appendix A details Calvin's compensation change history from hire to current:
- o Appendix B is ISS' valuation assumptions of CEO equity mix:
- o Appendix C is the compensation peer group used to benchmark CEO pay.
- o Appendix D is Calvin's compensation arrangements against the ISS peer group.
- o Appendix E details the peer group's stock ownership guidelines (SOG) for CEO.
- o
- o Appendix G shows Calvin's tally sheet; detailing all elements of his compensation from F2020-F2024.

## CEO Equity Mix

## Proposed F2025 Equity Mix

To provide strong upside opportunity, better alignment to market equity mix we are proposing a shift in CEO equity mix by increasing the weighting of PSUs. In addition; this would result in his mix being considered 'performance based' from an ISS perspective.

- o Increasing PSUs means a greater portion of compensation is directly tied to the achievement of multi-year financial goals.
- o As PSUs are granted as whole shares; retain value even during periods of short-term stock price volatility. This encourages a focus on sustained performance over the long-term. they

## Market Data

Agreater weighting on PSUs in CEO equity mix is market prevalent amongst our peer group. On average; PSUs account for nearly 60% of the CEO equity mix.

- o Three peers currently have the same proposed equity mix (The Gap; Chipotle &amp; Williams-Sonoma).
- o Five peers have a weighting ~60% PSUs (Starbucks; Ross; Gap, Skechers; Williams-Sonoma; Chipotle)
- o Three peers have a PSU weighting of more than 70% (Adidas AG; Puma and Ralph Lauren).
- o Options remain prevalent amongst our peers (10/19 peers); however most have a weighting under 50%.

## ISS

As previously discussed with the Committee; ISS' valuation of our CEO equity award does not align with our internal valuation approach due to the difference in expected life used in the Black-Scholes valuation:

This difference changes the weighting of the CEO's equity mix to be more heavily weighted towards options (~57% vs. 50%), leading to ISS' assessment that our mix is less than 50% performance-driven:

Increasing the weighting of PSUs in the CEO's equity mix from 50% to 60% is expectedto result in a favorable assessment from ISS; therefore increasing the CEOs performance weighting from 43% to 53%.

## B - ISS' CEO Equity Mix

## Previous Assessment

ISS' valuation of our CEO equity award does not align with our internal valuation approach due to the difference in expected life used in the Black-Scholes valuation:

- o In previous years; we had used 3.75 years as the expected life assumption for all our employees' stock options grants which is a disclosed figure in our annual report (10-K). This figure is based on the historical experience of past awards and considers the expected exercise behavior of future employees. We review this annually alongside all inputs to our Black-Scholes valuation such as share price volatility.
- o ISS' methodology is to value the CEOs stock option awards using the full option term of 7 years.
- o This difference in expected life methodology changes the weighting of the CEO's equity mix to be more heavily weighted towards options (~57% vs. 50%) , leading to ISS' assessment that our mix is less than 50% performance-driven.

## Future Assessment

If the proposed changes to CEO target and equity mix are approved; we can also expect ISS' valuation of our CEO awards to change.

- o For options granted in F2025, the expected life will be 4 years as the historical expected life for active employees in the last few years has increased.
- o If there is a change in ISS valuation; it will be captured in the F2025 Proxy to be filed in April 2026.
